[src:service-workers/cachestorage] The **`CacheStorage`** interface represents the storage for `Cache` objects.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] Use `CacheStorage.open()` to obtain a `Cache` instance.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] Use `CacheStorage.match()` to check if a given `Request` is a key in any of the `Cache` objects that the `CacheStorage` object tracks.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] You can access `CacheStorage` through the `Window.caches` property in windows or through the `WorkerGlobalScope.caches` property in workers.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] Checks if a given `Request` is a key in any of the `Cache` objects that the `CacheStorage` object tracks, and returns a `Promise` that resolves to that match.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] Returns a `Promise` that resolves to `true` if a `Cache` object matching the `cacheName` exists.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] Finds the `Cache` object matching the `cacheName`, and if found, deletes the `Cache` object and returns a `Promise` that resolves to `true`.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] If no `Cache` object is found, it resolves to `false`.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] Returns a `Promise` that will resolve with an array containing strings corresponding to all of the named `Cache` objects tracked by the `CacheStorage`.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] Use this method to iterate over a list of all the `Cache` objects.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] This code snippet is from the MDN simple service worker example (see simple service worker running live.) This service worker script waits for an `install` event to fire, then runs `waitUntil` to handle the install process for the app.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] This consists of calling `CacheStorage.open` to create a new cache, then using `Cache.addAll` to add a series of assets to it.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] In the second code block, we wait for a `FetchEvent` to fire.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] If this fails (e.g., because the network is down), return a fallback response.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] Finally, return whatever the custom response ended up being equal to, using `FetchEvent.respondWith`.
[src:service-workers/cachestorage] This snippet shows how the API can be used outside of a service worker context, and uses the `await` operator for much more readable code.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Service workers essentially act as proxy servers that sit between web applications, the browser, and the network (when available).
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] They are intended, among other things, to enable the creation of effective offline experiences, intercept network requests, and take appropriate action based on whether the network is available, and update assets residing on the server.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] They will also allow access to push notifications and background sync APIs.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] A service worker is an event-driven worker registered against an origin and a path.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Service workers run in a worker context: they therefore have no DOM access and run on a different thread to the main JavaScript that powers your app.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] They are non-blocking and designed to be fully asynchronous.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] As a consequence, APIs such as synchronous XHR and Web Storage can't be used inside a service worker.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Service workers can't import JavaScript modules dynamically, and `import()` will throw an error if it is called in a service worker global scope.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Static imports using the `import` statement are allowed.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Service workers are only available in secure contexts: this means that their document is served over HTTPS, although browsers also treat `http://localhost` as a secure context, to facilitate local development.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] HTTP connections are susceptible to malicious code injection by man in the middle attacks, and such attacks could be worse if allowed access to these powerful APIs.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] A service worker is first registered using the `ServiceWorkerContainer.register()` method.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] If successful, your service worker will be downloaded to the client and attempt installation/activation (see below) for URLs accessed by the user inside the whole origin, or a subset specified by you.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] The service worker is immediately downloaded when a user first accesses a service worker–controlled site/page.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Installation is attempted when the downloaded file is found to be new — either different to an existing service worker (byte-wise compared), or the first service worker encountered for this page/site.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] If this is the first time a service worker has been made available, installation is attempted, then after a successful installation, it is activated.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] If there is an existing service worker available, the new version is installed in the background, but not yet activated — at this point it is called the *worker in waiting*.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] It is only activated when there are no longer any pages loaded that are still using the old service worker.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] As soon as there are no more pages to be loaded, the new service worker activates (becoming the *active worker*).
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Activation can happen sooner using `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope.skipWaiting()` and existing pages can be claimed by the active worker using `Clients.claim()`.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] You can listen for the `install` event; a standard action is to prepare your service worker for usage when this fires, for example by creating a cache using the built-in storage API, and placing assets inside it that you'll want for running your app offline.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] The point where this event fires is generally a good time to clean up old caches and other things associated with the previous version of your service worker.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Your service worker can respond to requests using the `FetchEvent` event.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] You can modify the response to these requests in any way you want, using the `FetchEvent.respondWith()` method.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] For a complete tutorial to show how to build up your first basic example, read Using Service Workers.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Service workers can incur an unnecessary performance cost — when a page is loaded for the first time in a while, the browser has to wait for the service worker to start up and run to know what content to load and whether it should come from a cache or the network.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] If you already know ahead of time where certain content should be fetched from, you can bypass the service worker altogether and fetch resources immediately.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] The `InstallEvent.addRoutes()` method can be used to implement this use case and more.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] In the future, service workers will be able to do several other useful things for the web platform that will bring it closer to native app viability.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Represents the storage for `Request` / `Response` object pairs that are cached as part of the `ServiceWorker` life cycle.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Represents the storage for `Cache` objects.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] It provides a master directory of all the named caches that a `ServiceWorker` can access, and maintains a mapping of string names to corresponding `Cache` objects.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Represents the scope of a service worker client.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] A service worker client is either a document in a browser context or a `SharedWorker`, which is controlled by an active worker.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Represents a container for a list of `Client` objects; the main way to access the active service worker clients at the current origin.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Extends the lifetime of the `install` and `activate` events dispatched on the `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope`, as part of the service worker lifecycle.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] This ensures that any functional events (like `FetchEvent`) are not dispatched to the `ServiceWorker`, until it upgrades database schemas, and deletes outdated cache entries, etc.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] The event object of a `message` event fired on a service worker (when a channel message is received on the `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope` from another context) — extends the lifetime of such events.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] The parameter passed into the `onfetch` handler, `FetchEvent` represents a fetch action that is dispatched on the `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope` of a `ServiceWorker`.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] It contains information about the request and resulting response, and provides the `FetchEvent.respondWith()` method, which allows us to provide an arbitrary response back to the controlled page.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] The parameter passed into an `install` event handler function, the `InstallEvent` interface represents an install action that is dispatched on the `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope` of a `ServiceWorker`.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] As a child of `ExtendableEvent`, it ensures that functional events such as `FetchEvent` are not dispatched during installation.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Provides methods for managing the preloading of resources with a service worker.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Multiple browsing contexts (e.g., pages, workers, etc.) can be associated with the same `ServiceWorker` object.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Provides an object representing the service worker as an overall unit in the network ecosystem, including facilities to register, unregister, and update service workers, and access the state of service workers and their registrations.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Represents the global execution context of a service worker.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Represents a service worker registration.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Represents the scope of a service worker client that is a document in a browser context, controlled by an active worker.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] This is a special type of `Client` object, with some additional methods and properties available.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Returns the `CacheStorage` object associated with the current context.
[src:service-workers/service-worker-api] Returns a `ServiceWorkerContainer` object, which provides access to registration, removal, upgrade, and communication with the `ServiceWorker` objects for the associated document.
[src:service-workers/serviceworker] The **`serviceWorker`** read-only property of the `Navigator` interface returns the `ServiceWorkerContainer` object for the associated document, which provides access to registration, removal, upgrade, and communication with the `ServiceWorker`.
[src:service-workers/serviceworker] The feature may not be available in private mode.
[src:service-workers/serviceworker] Note that a worker can similarly access the `ServiceWorkerContainer` for a document using `WorkerNavigator.serviceWorker`.
[src:service-workers/serviceworker] This code checks if the browser supports service workers.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] One overriding problem that web users have suffered with for years is loss of connectivity.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The best web app in the world will provide a terrible user experience if you can't download it.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] There have been various attempts to create technologies to solve this problem, and some of the issues have been solved.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] But the overriding problem is that there wasn't a good overall control mechanism for asset caching and custom network requests.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Using a service worker you can set an app up to use cached assets first, thus providing a default experience even when offline, before then getting more data from the network (commonly known as "offline first").
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] This is already available with native apps, which is one of the main reasons native apps are often chosen over web apps.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] A service worker functions like a proxy server, allowing you to modify requests and responses replacing them with items from its own cache.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Service workers are enabled by default in all modern browsers.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] To run code using service workers, you'll need to serve your code via HTTPS — Service workers are restricted to running across HTTPS for security reasons.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] To host experiments, you can use a service such as GitHub, Netlify, Vercel, etc.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] In order to facilitate local development, `localhost` is considered a secure origin by browsers as well.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] An `install` event is always the first one sent to a service worker (this can be used to start the process of populating an IndexedDB, and caching site assets).
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] During this step, the application is preparing to make everything available for use offline.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] When the `install` handler completes, the service worker is considered installed.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] At this point a previous version of the service worker may be active and controlling open pages.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Because we don't want two different versions of the same service worker running at the same time, the new version is not yet active.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Once all pages controlled by the old version of the service worker have closed, it's safe to retire the old version, and the newly installed service worker receives an `activate` event.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The primary use of `activate` is to clean up resources used in previous versions of the service worker.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The new service worker can call `skipWaiting()` to ask to be activated immediately without waiting for open pages to be closed.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The new service worker will then receive `activate` immediately, and will take over any open pages.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] After activation, the service worker will now control pages, but only those that were opened after the `register()` is successful.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] In other words, documents will have to be reloaded to actually be controlled, because a document starts life with or without a service worker and maintains that for its lifetime.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] To override this default behavior and adopt open pages, a service worker can call `clients.claim()`.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Whenever a new version of a service worker is fetched, this cycle happens again and the remains of the previous version are cleaned during the new version's activation.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] To demonstrate just the very basics of registering and installing a service worker, we have created a demo called simple service worker, which is a simple Star Wars Lego image gallery.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] It uses a promise-powered function to read image data from a JSON object and load the images using `fetch()`, before displaying the images in a line down the page.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] It also registers, installs, and activates a service worker.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] You can see the source code on GitHub, and the simple service worker running live.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The first block of code in our app's JavaScript file — `app.js` — is as follows.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] This is our entry point into using service workers.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Next, we use the `ServiceWorkerContainer.register()` function to register the service worker for this site.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The `scope` parameter is optional, and can be used to specify the subset of your content that you want the service worker to control.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] In this case, we have specified `'/'`, which means all content under the app's origin.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] If you leave it out, it will default to this value anyway, but we specified it here for illustration purposes.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] This registers a service worker, which runs in a worker context, and therefore has no DOM access.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] A single service worker can control many pages.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Each time a page within your scope is loaded, the service worker is installed against that page and operates on it.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Bear in mind therefore that you need to be careful with global variables in the service worker script: each page doesn't get its own unique worker.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] After your service worker is registered, the browser will attempt to install then activate the service worker for your page/site.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The `install` event is the first event that is fired on service worker installation or update.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] It is emitted just once, immediately after registration is successfully completed, and is generally used to populate your browser's offline caching capabilities with the assets you need to run your app offline.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] To do this, we use Service Worker's storage API — `cache` — a global object on the service worker that allows us to store assets delivered by responses, and keyed by their requests.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] This API works in a similar way to the browser's standard cache, but it is specific to your domain.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The contents of the cache are kept until you clear them.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Inside `addResourcesToCache()` we use the `caches.open()` method to create a new cache called `v1`, which will be version 1 of our site resources cache.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Then we call a function `addAll()` on the created cache, which for its parameter takes an array of URLs to all the resources you want to cache.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The URLs are relative to the worker's location.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] If the promise is rejected, the installation fails, and the worker won't do anything.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] This is OK, as you can fix your code and then try again the next time registration occurs.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] After a successful installation, the service worker activates.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Now you've got your site assets cached, you need to tell service workers to do something with the cached content.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] You can attach a `fetch` event listener to the service worker, then call the `respondWith()` method on the event to hijack our HTTP responses and update them with your own content.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The matching is done via URL and various headers, just like with normal HTTP requests.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] So `caches.match(event.request)` is great when there is a match in the service worker cache, but what about cases when there isn't a match?
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] If we didn't provide any kind of failure handling, our promise would resolve with `undefined` and we wouldn't get anything returned.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] If the resources aren't in the cache, they are requested from the network.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Using a more elaborate strategy, we could not only request the resource from the network, but also save it into the cache so that later requests for that resource could be retrieved offline too.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] This would mean that if extra images were added to the Star Wars gallery, our app could automatically grab them and cache them.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] If the request URL is not available in the cache, we request the resource from the network request with `await fetch(request)`.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] After that, we put a clone of the response into the cache.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The `putInCache()` function uses `caches.open('v1')` and `cache.put()` to add the resource to the cache.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The original response is returned to the browser to be given to the page that called it.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Cloning the response is necessary because request and response streams can only be read once.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] In order to return the response to the browser and put it in the cache we have to clone it.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] So the original gets returned to the browser and the clone gets sent to the cache.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] What might look a bit weird is that the promise returned by `putInCache()` is not awaited.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The reason is that we don't want to wait until the response clone has been added to the cache before returning a response.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] However, we do need to call `event.waitUntil()` on the promise, to make sure the service worker doesn't terminate before the cache is populated.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The only trouble we have now is that if the request doesn't match anything in the cache, and the network is not available, our request will still fail.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] We have opted for this fallback image because the only updates that are likely to fail are new images, as everything else is depended on for installation in the `install` event listener we saw earlier.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] If enabled, the navigation preload feature starts downloading resources as soon as the fetch request is made, and in parallel with service worker activation.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] This ensures that download starts immediately on navigation to a page, rather than having to wait until the service worker is activated.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] That delay happens relatively rarely, but is unavoidable when it does happen, and may be significant.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Then use `event.preloadResponse` to wait for the preloaded resource to finish downloading in the `fetch` event handler.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Continuing the example from the previous sections, we insert the code to wait for the preloaded resource after the cache check, and before fetching from the network if that doesn't succeed.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Wait on `event.preloadResponse`, which is passed as `preloadResponsePromise` to the `cacheFirst()` function.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] If neither of these are defined then we go to the network.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Note that in this example we download and cache the same data for the resource whether it is downloaded "normally" or preloaded.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] You can instead choose to download and cache a different resource on preload.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] For more information see `NavigationPreloadManager` > Custom responses.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] If your service worker has previously been installed, but then a new version of the worker is available on refresh or page load, the new version is installed in the background, but not yet activated.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] As soon as there are no more such pages still loaded, the new service worker activates.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] While the service worker is being installed, the previous version is still responsible for fetches.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] The new version is installing in the background.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] We are calling the new cache `v2`, so the previous `v1` cache isn't disturbed.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] When no pages are using the previous version, the new worker activates and becomes responsible for fetches.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] As we saw in the last section, when you update a service worker to a new version, you'll create a new cache in its `install` event handler.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] While there are open pages that are controlled by the previous version of the worker, you need to keep both caches, because the previous version needs its version of the cache.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] You can use the `activate` event to remove data from the previous caches.
[src:service-workers/using-service-workers] Promises passed into `waitUntil()` will block other events until completion, so you can rest assured that your clean-up operation will have completed by the time you get your first `fetch` event on the new service worker.
